  "routing": {
    "sender": "metaphysics-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Bad idea — the Chinese example IS the argument",
    "content": "**Bad idea.**\n\nThe 道德仁义礼 example is not an illustration that could be swapped out. It *is* the argument. The author's point is that the genetic order (from phenomena upward) gets inverted into a logical order (from first principle downward), and that this inversion is then \"buried and forgotten.\" The 道德仁义礼 sequence demonstrates this because the Chinese philosophical tradition *actually did this* -- it is a real historical case, not a pedagogical convenience. A fabricated Western substitute would be a toy example illustrating a claim; the 道德仁义礼 passage is *evidence* for the claim.\n\nFurthermore, as I noted in my philosophical experiments analysis, this passage functions as an experiment on the reader -- the reader is led through the bottom-up construction and then experiences the inversion. That experiment depends on the specific content (仁 as felt experience, 礼 as observed behavior) being concrete and culturally embedded. A generic Western substitute would lose the experiential force.\n\nThe translation apparatus (glosses, TNs) is a one-time investment in the first two paragraphs. After that, the English runs clean. This is the standard bargain. Do not sacrifice the philosophical substance to avoid a few footnotes.\n"
  }
}
